"Reiczigel J., Solymosi N., Könyves L., Maróti-Agóts Á., Kern A., Bartyik J.","Examination of heat stress caused milk production loss by the use of temperature- Humidity indices [A ho″stressz okozta tejtermelés-kiesés vizsgálata hömérséklet-páratartalom indexek alkalmazásával]",2009,"Magyar Allatorvosok Lapja","131","3",,"127","144",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-62749098746&partnerID=40&md5=f95118acababf888a7e4e1dd150f4c53","SZIE-ÁOTK, Biomatematikai es Számftástechnikai Tanszék, István u. 2, H-1078 Budapest, Hungary; MTA-BCE Alkalmazkodás, A Klímaváltozáshoz Kutatócsoport; SZIE-ÁOTK, Állathigiéniai, Allomany-egeszsegtani es Allatorvosi Etologiai Tanszek, Hungary; SZIE-ÁOTK, Állattenyésztési, Takarmányozástani es Laborállat-tudományi Intézet, Hungary; Enyingi Agrár Zrt","Reiczigel, J., SZIE-ÁOTK, Biomatematikai es Számftástechnikai Tanszék, István u. 2, H-1078 Budapest, Hungary; Solymosi, N., MTA-BCE Alkalmazkodás, A Klímaváltozáshoz Kutatócsoport; Könyves, L., SZIE-ÁOTK, Állathigiéniai, Allomany-egeszsegtani es Allatorvosi Etologiai Tanszek, Hungary; Maróti-Agóts, Á., SZIE-ÁOTK, Állattenyésztési, Takarmányozástani es Laborállat-tudományi Intézet, Hungary; Kern, A., MTA-BCE Alkalmazkodás, A Klímaváltozáshoz Kutatócsoport; Bartyik, J., Enyingi Agrár Zrt","Global warming has caused increasing concern about heat stress. In cattle, heat stress affects both the production and reproduction negatively. Several temperature- humidity indices (THI) are in use to quantify the degree of heat stress. In this study, the authors compared six such indices, together with their thresholds indicating danger of heat stress, for applicability in Hungary. Data from the data base of the cattle farm of Enyingi Agrar Inc. in Kiscserpuszta, Hungary were used in the study. Those cows were selected (n=1007), which had production records on at least 600 days in the study period (1.10. 2001 to 16. 3. 2004). The authors found that two of the six indices worked well on these data in the sense they were able to indicate reduction of milk production due to heat stress. The results show that heat stress affects the production immediately, and even a single heat stress day causes an average milk loss of 1.5 to 2 liters per cow per day (5-10% of the daily production). One to three-day heat stress periods were found to result in about the same milk loss.",,"Bos",,,,,,"ARMSTRONG, D.V., Heat stress interaction with shade and cooling (1994) J. Dairy Sci, 77, pp. 2044-2050; BIANCA, W., Relative importance of dry and wet-bulb temperature in causing heat stress in cattle (1962) Nature, 195, p. 251; BOHMANOVA, J., MISZTAL, I., COLE, J.B., Tempera- ture-humidity indices as indicators of milk production losses due to heat stress (2007) J. Dairy Sci, 90, pp. 1947-1956; BOURAOUI, R., lAHMAR, M., The relationship of temperature-humidity index with milk production of dairy cows in a mediterranean climate (2002) Anim. Res, 57, pp. 479-491; CASIMIRO, E., CALHEIROS, J., National assessment of human health effects of climate change in Portugal: Approach and key findings (2006) Environ. Health Perspect, 114, pp. 1950-1956; FINOCCHIARO, R., VAN KAAM, J.B.C.H.M., Effect of heat stress on production of mediterranean dairy sheep (2005) J. Dairy Sci, 88, pp. 1855-1864; GLOSTER, J., MELLOR, P.S., Will bluetongue come on the wind to the United Kingdom in 2007 (2007) Vet. Rec, 760, pp. 422-426; HUHNKE, R.L., MCCOWAN, L.C., Determining the frequency and duration of elevated temperature-humidity index (2004) Appl. Eng. Agric, 20, pp. 95-99; JAYKUS, L.-A., WOOLRIDGE, M., (2008) Climate change: Implications for food safety, , FAO; MORSE, D., DE LORENZO, M.A., Climatic effects on occurence of clinical mastitis (1988) J. Dairy Sci, 71, pp. 848-853; MORTON, J.M., TRANTER, W.P., Effects of environmental heat on conception rates in lactating dairy cows: Critical periods of exposure (2007) J. Dairy Sci, 90, pp. 2271-2278; A guide to environmental reasearch on animals (1971),